ia) **·** [scholar](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Claude+Shannon%22) **·** [JSTOR](https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Claude+Shannon%22&acc=on&wc=on) _( April 2026)__([Learn how and when to remove this message](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal \"Help:Maintenance template removal\"))_  |  \n| --- | --- |  \nAmerican mathematician (1916–2001)  \n| Claude Shannon |  \n| --- |  \n|  [![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/C.E._Shannon._Tekniska_museet_43069_%282x3_crop%29.jpg/250px-C.E._Shannon._Tekniska_museet_43069_%282x3_crop%29.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:C.E._Shannon._Tekniska_museet_43069_\\(2x3_crop\\).jpg)Shannon c. 1950s  |  \n| Born  |  Claude Elwood Shannon   \n(1916-04-30)April 30, 1916  \n[Petoskey, Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petoskey,_Michigan \"Petoskey, Michigan\"), U.S.  |  \n| Died  | February 24, 2001(2001-02-24) (aged 84)  \n[Medford, Massachusetts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medford,_Massachusetts \"Medford, Massachusetts\"), U.S.  |  \n| Education  |  [University of Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Michigan \"University of Michigan\") ([BS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bachelor_of_Science \"Bachelor of Science\"), [BSE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bachelor_of_Engineering \"Bachelor of Engineering\"))  \n[Massachusetts Institute of Technology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology \"Massachusetts Institute of Technology\") ([MS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Master_of_Science \"Master of Science\"), [PhD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PhD \"PhD\"))  |  \n| Known for  | \n  * [Information theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory \"Information theory\")\n  * [Artificial intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence \"Artificial intelligence\")\n  * [Boolean algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra \"Boolean algebra\")\n  * [Binary code](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_code \"Binary code\")\n  * [Data compression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_compression \"Data compression\")\n  * [Digital electronics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_electronics \"Digital electronics\")\n  * [Entropy in information theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_\\(information_theory\\) \"Entropy \\(information theory\\)\")\n  * [Logic gate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_gate \"Logic gate\")\n  * [Pulse-code modulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-code_modulation \"Pulse-code modulation\")\n  * [Sampling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_\\(signal_processing\\) \"Sampling \\(signal processing\\)\")\n  * [Symmetric-key cryptography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric-key_cryptography \"Symmetric-key cryptography\")\n  * [Switching circuit theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Switching_circuit_theory \"Switching circuit theory\")\n  * [Units of information](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_information \"Units of information\")\n  * [Wearable computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wearable_computer \"Wearable computer\")\n\n |  \n| Spouses  | \n  * [Norma Levor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norma_Barzman \"Norma Barzman\") ​ ​(m. 1940; div. 1941)​\n  * [Betty Shannon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Shannon \"Betty Shannon\") ​(m. 1949⁠–⁠2001)​\n\n |  \n| Awards  | \n  * [Alfred Noble Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Noble_Prize \"Alfred Noble Prize\") (1939)\n  * [Morris Liebmann Memorial Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morris_Liebmann_Memorial_Prize \"Morris Liebmann Memorial Prize\") (1949)\n  * [Stuart Ballantine Medal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_Ballantine_Medal \"Stuart Ballantine Medal\") (1955)\n  * [IEEE Medal of Honor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Medal_of_Honor \"IEEE Medal of Honor\") (1966)\n  * [National Medal of Science](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Medal_of_Science \"National Medal of Science\") (1966)\n  * [Harvey Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Prize \"Harvey Prize\") (1972)\n  * [Claude E. Shannon Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_E._Shannon_Award \"Claude E. Shannon Award\") (1973)\n  * [Harold Pender Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Pender_Award \"Harold Pender Award\") (1978)\n  * [John Fritz Medal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Fritz_Medal \"John Fritz Medal\") (1983)\n  * [Kyoto Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyoto_Prize \"Kyoto Prize\") (1985)\n  * [Audio Engineering Society Gold Medal Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Audio_Engineering_Society#Awardees_in_chronological_order \"Audio Engineering Society\") (1985)\n  * [Marconi Society Lifetime Achievement Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marconi_Prize \"Marconi Prize\") (2000)\n  * [National Inventors Hall of Fame](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Inventors_Hall_of_Fame \"National Inventors Hall of Fame\") (2004)\n\n |  \n| **Scientific career** |  \n| Fields  |  [Mathematics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics \"Mathematics\"), [computer science](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science \"Computer science\"), [electronic engineering](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_engineering \"Electronic engineering\"), [artificial intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence \"Artificial intelligence\")  |  \n| Institutions  | \n  * [Bell Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\")\n  * Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n  * [Institute for Advanced Study](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_for_Advanced_Study \"Institute for Advanced Study\")\n\n |  \n| [Theses](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thesis \"Thesis\")  | \n  * _[A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits](https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/11173) _ (1937)\n  * _[An Algebra for Theoretical Genetics](https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/11174)_ (1940)\n\n |  \n| [Doctoral advisor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctoral_advisor \"Doctoral advisor\")  | [Frank Lauren Hitchcock](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Lauren_Hitchcock \"Frank Lauren Hitchcock\")  |  \n| Doctoral students  | \n  * [Elwyn Berlekamp](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elwyn_Berlekamp \"Elwyn Berlekamp\")\n  * [Danny Hillis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danny_Hillis \"Danny Hillis\")\n  * [Leonard Kleinrock](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonard_Kleinrock \"Leonard Kleinrock\")\n  * [Ivan Sutherland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Sutherland \"Ivan Sutherland\")\n  * [Bert Sutherland](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bert_Sutherland \"Bert Sutherland\")\n\n |  \n| Other notable students  | [Chung Laung Liu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chung_Laung_Liu \"Chung Laung Liu\")  |  \n|   |  \n**Claude Elwood Shannon** (April 30, 1916 – February 24, 2001) was an American [polymath](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymath \"Polymath\") who was a mathematician, electrical engineer, computer scientist, cryptographer, and inventor known as the \"father of [information theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory \"Information theory\")\", and the man who laid the foundations of the [Information Age](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_Age \"Information Age\").[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-BulletinESA-1)[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-QuantaMagazine-2)[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-NewYorker4.30.16-3)\nShannon was the first to describe the use of [Boolean algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra \"Boolean algebra\")—essential to all [digital electronic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_electronic \"Digital electronic\") circuits—and helped found the field of [artificial intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence \"Artificial intelligence\").[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-PortraitsInSilicon-4)[[5]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-bmfrs-5)[[6]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEESpectrum4.27.16-6) The roboticist [Rodney Brooks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Brooks \"Rodney Brooks\") declared Shannon the 20th century engineer who contributed the most to 21st century technologies,[[7]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEESpectrum1.25.22-7) and the mathematician [Solomon W. Golomb](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_W._Golomb \"Solomon W. Golomb\") described his intellectual achievement as \"one of the greatest of the twentieth century\".[[8]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-8)\nAt the [University of Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Michigan \"University of Michigan\"), Shannon [dual-degreed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_degree \"Dual degree\"), graduating with a Bachelor of Science in electrical engineering and another in mathematics, both in 1936. As a 21-year-old [master's degree](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Master%27s_degree \"Master's degree\") student in electrical engineering at [MIT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT \"MIT\"), his 1937 thesis, \"[A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Symbolic_Analysis_of_Relay_and_Switching_Circuits \"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits\")\", demonstrated that electrical applications of [Boolean algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra \"Boolean algebra\") could construct any logical numerical relationship,[[9]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune-9) thereby establishing the theory behind [digital computing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_computing \"Digital computing\") and [digital circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_circuits \"Digital circuits\").[[10]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-10) Called by some the most important master's thesis of all time,[[9]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune-9) it is the \"birth certificate of the digital revolution\",[[11]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-11) and started him in a lifetime of work that led him to win a [Kyoto Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyoto_Prize \"Kyoto Prize\") in 1985.[[12]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-12) He graduated from MIT in 1940 with a PhD in mathematics;[[13]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEEITS-13) his thesis focusing on [genetics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetics \"Genetics\") contained important results, while initially going unpublished.[[14]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEETransactions-14)\nShannon contributed to the field of [cryptanalysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptanalysis \"Cryptanalysis\") for national defense of the United States during [World War II](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II \"World War II\"), including his fundamental work on codebreaking and secure [telecommunications](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telecommunications \"Telecommunications\"), writing a [paper](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_Theory_of_Secrecy_Systems \"Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems\") which is considered one of the foundational pieces of modern cryptography,[[15]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-15) with his work described as \"a turning point, and marked the closure of classical cryptography and the beginning of modern cryptography\". His work was foundational for [symmetric-key cryptography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric-key_cryptography \"Symmetric-key cryptography\"), including the work of [Horst Feistel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horst_Feistel \"Horst Feistel\"), the [Data Encryption Standard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_Encryption_Standard \"Data Encryption Standard\") (DES), and the [Advanced Encryption Standard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advanced_Encryption_Standard \"Advanced Encryption Standard\") (AES).[[16]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-16) As a result, Shannon has been called the \"founding father of modern cryptography\".[[17]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-17)\nHis 1948 paper \"[A Mathematical Theory of Communication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Mathematical_Theory_of_Communication \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\")\" laid the foundations for the field of information theory,[[13]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEEITS-13)[[18]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune2-18) referred to as a \"blueprint for the digital era\" by electrical engineer [Robert G. Gallager](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_G._Gallager \"Robert G. Gallager\")[[19]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-TechReview7.1.01-19) and \"the [Magna Carta](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magna_Carta \"Magna Carta\") of the Information Age\" by _[Scientific American](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_American \"Scientific American\")_.[[20]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-20)[[21]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-21) Golomb compared Shannon's influence on the digital age to that which \"the inventor of the alphabet has had on literature\".[[18]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune2-18) Shannon is also regarded as the most important post-1948 contributor to the theory. Advancements across multiple scientific disciplines utilized Shannon's theory—including the invention of the [compact disc](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_disc \"Compact disc\"), the development of the [Internet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet \"Internet\"), the commercialization of mobile telephony, and the understanding of [black holes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_hole \"Black hole\").[[22]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-22)[[23]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-23) He formally introduced the term \"[bit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit \"Bit\")\",[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-QuantaMagazine-2)[[24]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-24) and was a co-inventor of both [pulse-code modulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-code_modulation \"Pulse-code modulation\") and the first [wearable computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wearable_computer \"Wearable computer\"). He also invented the [signal-flow graph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal-flow_graph \"Signal-flow graph\"). \nShannon joined the [Central Intelligence Agency](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Intelligence_Agency \"Central Intelligence Agency\")'s Special Cryptologic Advisory Group in 1951. From 1956 to 1978, he was a professor at MIT. He also made numerous contributions to the field of artificial intelligence,[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-PortraitsInSilicon-4) including co-organizing the 1956 [Dartmouth workshop](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dartmouth_workshop \"Dartmouth workshop\"), considered to be the discipline's founding event,[[25]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-25)[[26]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Solomonoff-26) and papers on the programming of chess computers.[[27]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-CompSimBehavior-27)[[28]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-DebuggingGameHist-28) His Theseus machine was the first electrical device to learn by trial and error, being one of the first examples of artificial intelligence.[[7]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEESpectrum1.25.22-7)[[29]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT-29)\n## Biography\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=1 \"Edit section: Biography\")]\n### Childhood\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=2 \"Edit section: Childhood\")]\nThe Shannon family lived in [Gaylord, Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaylord,_Michigan \"Gaylord, Michigan\"), and Claude was born in a hospital in nearby [Petoskey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petoskey,_Michigan \"Petoskey, Michigan\").[[5]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-bmfrs-5) His father, Claude Sr. (1862–1934), was a businessman and, for a while, a judge of [probate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probate \"Probate\") in Gaylord. His mother, Mabel Wolf Shannon (1880–1945), was a language teacher, who also served as the principal of [Gaylord High School](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaylord_High_School \"Gaylord High School\").[[30]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-FOOTNOTESloaneWyner1993xi-30) Claude Sr. was a descendant of [New Jersey settlers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colonial_history_of_New_Jersey \"Colonial history of New Jersey\"), while Mabel was a child of German immigrants.[[5]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-bmfrs-5) Shannon's family was active in their Methodist Church during his youth.[[31]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Soni_Goodman_2017_p._6-31)\nMost of the first 16 years of Shannon's life were spent in Gaylord, where he attended public school, graduating from Gaylord High School in 1932. Shannon showed an inclination towards mechanical and electrical subjects. His best subjects were science and mathematics. At home, he constructed such devices as models of planes, a radio-controlled model boat and a barbed-wire [telegraph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telegraph \"Telegraph\") system to a friend's house a half-mile away.[[32]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-32) While growing up, he also worked as a messenger for the [Western Union](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Union \"Western Union\") company. \nShannon's childhood hero was [Thomas Edison](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Edison \"Thomas Edison\"), whom he later learned was a distant cousin. Both Shannon and Edison were descendants of [John Ogden](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ogden_\\(colonist\\) \"John Ogden \\(colonist\\)\") (1609–1682), a colonial leader and an ancestor of many distinguished people.[[33]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT_obituary-33)[[34]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-sloane-wyner93-34)\n### Logic circuits\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=3 \"Edit section: Logic circuits\")]\nIn 1932, Shannon entered the [University of Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Michigan \"University of Michigan\"), where he was introduced to the work of [George Boole](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Boole \"George Boole\"). He graduated in 1936 with two bachelor's degrees: one in electrical engineering and the other in mathematics.[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\nIn 1936, Shannon began his graduate studies in electrical engineering at the [Massachusetts Institute of Technology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology \"Massachusetts Institute of Technology\") (MIT), where he worked on [Vannevar Bush](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vannevar_Bush \"Vannevar Bush\")'s [differential analyzer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_analyzer \"Differential analyzer\"), which was an early [analog computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analog_computer \"Analog computer\") that was composed of electromechanical parts and could solve [differential equations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation \"Differential equation\").[[35]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-35) While studying the complicated _ad hoc_ circuits of this analyzer, Shannon designed [switching circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Switching_circuit \"Switching circuit\") based on [Boole's concepts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra \"Boolean algebra\"). In 1937, he wrote his master's degree thesis, _[A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Symbolic_Analysis_of_Relay_and_Switching_Circuits \"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits\"),_[[36]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SymbolicAnalysis-36) with a paper from this thesis published in 1938.[[36]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SymbolicAnalysis-36) A revolutionary work for [switching circuit theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Switching_circuit_theory \"Switching circuit theory\"), in it Shannon diagramed switching circuits that could implement the essential operators of [Boolean algebra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_\\(logic\\) \"Boolean algebra \\(logic\\)\"). Then he proved that his switching circuits could be used to simplify the arrangement of the [electromechanical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromechanical \"Electromechanical\") [relays](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relay \"Relay\") that were used during that time in [telephone call routing switches](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_switched_telephone_network \"Public switched telephone network\"). Next, he expanded this concept, proving that these circuits could solve all problems that Boolean algebra could solve. In the last chapter, he presented diagrams of several circuits, including a digital 4-bit full adder.[[36]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SymbolicAnalysis-36) His work differed significantly from the work of previous engineers such as [Akira Nakashima](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akira_Nakashima \"Akira Nakashima\"), who still relied on the existent circuit theory of the time and took a grounded approach. Shannon's ideas were more abstract and relied on mathematics, thereby breaking new ground with his work, with his approach dominating modern-day electrical engineering.[[37]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-37)\nUsing electrical switches to implement logic is the fundamental concept that underlies all [electronic digital computers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer \"Computer\"). Shannon's work became the foundation of [digital circuit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_circuit \"Digital circuit\") design, as it became widely known in the electrical engineering community during and after World War II. The theoretical rigor of Shannon's work superseded the _ad hoc_ methods that had prevailed previously. In 1987, [Howard Gardner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Gardner \"Howard Gardner\") hailed Shannon's thesis \"possibly the most important, and also the most famous, master's thesis of the century.\"[[38]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-38) [Herman Goldstine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herman_Goldstine \"Herman Goldstine\") described it in 1972 as \"surely ... one of the most important master's theses ever written ... It helped to change digital circuit design from an art to a science.\"[[39]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-39) One of the reviewers of his work commented that \"To the best of my knowledge, this is the first application of the methods of symbolic logic to so practical an engineering problem. From the point of view of originality I rate the paper as outstanding.\"[[40]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-40) Shannon's master's thesis won the [1939 Alfred Noble Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Noble_Prize#Recipients \"Alfred Noble Prize\"). \nShannon received his PhD in mathematics from MIT in 1940.[[33]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT_obituary-33) [Vannevar Bush](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vannevar_Bush \"Vannevar Bush\") had suggested that Shannon should work on his dissertation at the [Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cold_Spring_Harbor_Laboratory \"Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory\"), in order to develop a mathematical formulation for [Mendelian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregor_Mendel \"Gregor Mendel\") [genetics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetics \"Genetics\"). This research resulted in Shannon's PhD thesis, called _An Algebra for Theoretical Genetics_.[[41]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-41) However, the thesis went unpublished after Shannon lost interest, but it did contain important results.[[14]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEETransactions-14) Notably, he was one of the first to apply an algebraic framework to study theoretical population genetics.[[42]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-42) In addition, Shannon devised a general expression for the distribution of several linked traits in a population after multiple generations under a random mating system, which was original at the time,[[43]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-43) with the new theorem unworked out by other [population geneticists](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_genetics \"Population genetics\") of the time.[[44]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-44)\nIn 1940, Shannon became a National Research Fellow at the [Institute for Advanced Study](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_for_Advanced_Study \"Institute for Advanced Study\") in [Princeton, New Jersey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princeton,_New_Jersey \"Princeton, New Jersey\"). In Princeton, Shannon had the opportunity to discuss his ideas with influential scientists and mathematicians such as [Hermann Weyl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Weyl \"Hermann Weyl\") and [John von Neumann](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann \"John von Neumann\"), and he also had occasional encounters with [Albert Einstein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein \"Albert Einstein\") and [Kurt Gödel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurt_G%C3%B6del \"Kurt Gödel\"). Shannon worked freely across disciplines, and this ability may have contributed to his later development of mathematical information theory.[[45]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-45)\n### Wartime research\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=4 \"Edit section: Wartime research\")]\nShannon had worked at [Bell Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\") for a few months in the summer of 1937,[[46]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-46) and returned there to work on [fire-control systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fire-control_system \"Fire-control system\") and [cryptography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography \"Cryptography\") during World War II, under a contract with section D-2 (Control Systems section) of the [National Defense Research Committee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Defense_Research_Committee \"National Defense Research Committee\") (NDRC). \nShannon is credited with the invention of [signal-flow graphs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal-flow_graph \"Signal-flow graph\"), in 1942. He discovered the topological gain formula while investigating the functional operation of an analog computer.[[47]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-47)\nFor two months early in 1943, Shannon came into contact with the leading British mathematician [Alan Turing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing \"Alan Turing\"). Turing had been posted to Washington to share with the [U.S. Navy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Navy \"U.S. Navy\")'s cryptanalytic service the methods used by the [Government Code and Cypher School](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_Code_and_Cypher_School \"Government Code and Cypher School\") at [Bletchley Park](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bletchley_Park \"Bletchley Park\") to break the cyphers used by the _[Kriegsmarine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kriegsmarine \"Kriegsmarine\")_ [U-boats](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U-boat \"U-boat\") in the north Atlantic Ocean.[[48]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Hodges1992-48) He was also interested in the encipherment of speech and to this end spent time at Bell Labs. Shannon and Turing met at teatime in the cafeteria.[[48]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Hodges1992-48) Turing showed Shannon his 1936 paper that defined what is now known as the \"[universal Turing machine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Turing_machine \"Universal Turing machine\")\".[[49]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-49)[[50]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-50) This impressed Shannon, as many of its ideas complemented his own.[[51]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-51)\nShannon and his team developed anti-aircraft systems that tracked enemy missiles and planes, while also determining the paths for intercepting missiles.[[52]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-52)\nIn 1945, as the war was coming to an end, the NDRC was issuing a summary of technical reports as a last step prior to its eventual closing down. Inside the volume on fire control, a special essay titled _Data Smoothing and Prediction in Fire-Control Systems_ , coauthored by Shannon, [Ralph Beebe Blackman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralph_Beebe_Blackman \"Ralph Beebe Blackman\"), and [Hendrik Wade Bode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hendrik_Wade_Bode \"Hendrik Wade Bode\"), formally treated the problem of smoothing the data in fire-control by analogy with \"the problem of separating a signal from interfering noise in communications systems.\"[[53]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-53) In other words, it modeled the problem in terms of [data](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_processing \"Data processing\") and [signal processing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_processing \"Signal processing\") and thus heralded the coming of the [Information Age](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_Age \"Information Age\").[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\nShannon's work on cryptography was even more closely related to his later publications on [communication theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_theory \"Communication theory\").[[54]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-54) At the close of the war, he prepared a classified memorandum for [Bell Telephone Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Telephone_Labs \"Bell Telephone Labs\") entitled \"A Mathematical Theory of Cryptography\", dated September 1945. A declassified version of this paper was published in 1949 as \"[Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_Theory_of_Secrecy_Systems \"Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems\")\" in the _[Bell System Technical Journal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_System_Technical_Journal \"Bell System Technical Journal\")_. This paper incorporated many of the concepts and mathematical formulations that also appeared in his _[A Mathematical Theory of Communication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Mathematical_Theory_of_Communication \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\")_. Shannon said that his wartime insights into communication theory and cryptography developed simultaneously, and that \"they were so close together you couldn't separate them\".[[55]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-55) In a footnote near the beginning of the classified report, Shannon announced his intention to \"develop these results … in a forthcoming memorandum on the transmission of information.\"[[56]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-56)\nWhile he was at Bell Labs, Shannon proved that the [cryptographic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptographic \"Cryptographic\") [one-time pad](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-time_pad \"One-time pad\") is unbreakable in his classified research that was later published in 1949. The same article also proved that any unbreakable system must have essentially the same characteristics as the one-time pad: the key must be truly random, as large as the plaintext, never reused in whole or part, and kept secret.[[57]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-57)\n### Information theory\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=5 \"Edit section: Information theory\")]\nIn 1948, the promised memorandum appeared as \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\", an article in two parts in the July and October issues of the _Bell System Technical Journal_. This work focuses on the problem of how best to encode the message a sender wants to transmit. Shannon developed [information entropy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_entropy \"Information entropy\") as a measure of the information content in a message, which is a measure of uncertainty reduced by the message. In so doing, he essentially invented the field of [information theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory \"Information theory\").[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\nThe book _The Mathematical Theory of Communication_[[58]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MathTheoryCommunication-58) reprints Shannon's 1948 article and [Warren Weaver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warren_Weaver \"Warren Weaver\")'s popularization of it, which is accessible to the non-specialist. Weaver pointed out that the word \"information\" in communication theory is not related to what you do say, but to what you could say. That is, information is a measure of one's freedom of choice when one selects a message. Shannon's concepts were also popularized, subject to his own proofreading, in [John Robinson Pierce](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Robinson_Pierce \"John Robinson Pierce\")'s _Symbols, Signals, and Noise_.[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\nInformation theory's fundamental contribution to [natural language processing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_processing \"Natural language processing\") and [computational linguistics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_linguistics \"Computational linguistics\") was further established in 1951, in his article \"Prediction and Entropy of Printed English\", showing upper and lower bounds of entropy on the statistics of English – giving a statistical foundation to language analysis. In addition, he proved that treating [space](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_\\(punctuation\\) \"Space \\(punctuation\\)\") as the 27th letter of the alphabet actually lowers uncertainty in written language, providing a clear quantifiable link between cultural practice and probabilistic cognition.[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\nAnother notable paper published in 1949 is \"[Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_Theory_of_Secrecy_Systems \"Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems\")\", a declassified version of his wartime work on the mathematical theory of cryptography, in which he proved that all theoretically unbreakable cyphers must have the same requirements as the one-time pad. He is credited with the introduction of [sampling theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist%E2%80%93Shannon_sampling_theorem \"Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem\"), which he had derived as early as 1940,[[59]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-59) and which is concerned with representing a continuous-time signal from a (uniform) discrete set of samples. This theory was essential in enabling telecommunications to move from analog to digital transmissions systems in the 1960s and later. He further wrote a paper in 1956 regarding coding for a noisy channel, which also became a classic paper in the field of information theory.[[60]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEEAnnalsComp-60) However, also in 1956 he wrote a one-page editorial for the \"IRE Transactions on Information Theory\" entitled \"The Bandwagon\" which he began by observing: \"Information theory has, in the last few years, become something of a scientific bandwagon\" and which he concluded by warning: \"Only by maintaining a thoroughly scientific attitude can we achieve real progress in communication theory and consolidate our present position.\"[[61]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-61)\nClaude Shannon's influence has been immense in the field, for example, in a 1973 collection of the key papers in the field of information theory, he was author or coauthor of 12 of the 49 papers cited, while no one else appeared more than three times. Even beyond his original paper in 1948, he is still regarded as the most important post-1948 contributor to the theory.[[62]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-62)\nIn May 1951, [Mervin Kelly](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mervin_Kelly \"Mervin Kelly\") received a request from the director of the [CIA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Intelligence_Agency \"Central Intelligence Agency\"), general [Walter Bedell Smith](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Bedell_Smith \"Walter Bedell Smith\"), regarding Shannon and the need for him, as Shannon was regarded as, based on \"the best authority\", the \"most eminently qualified scientist in the particular field concerned\".[[63]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Soni_Goodman_2017_p._63-63) As a result of the request, Shannon became part of the CIA's Special Cryptologic Advisory Group or SCAG.[[63]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Soni_Goodman_2017_p._63-63)\nIn his time at Bell Labs, he also co-developed [pulse-code modulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-code_modulation \"Pulse-code modulation\") alongside [Bernard M. Oliver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_M._Oliver \"Bernard M. Oliver\"), and [John R. Pierce](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_R._Pierce \"John R. Pierce\").[[64]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-64)[[65]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-65)\n### Artificial intelligence\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=6 \"Edit section: Artificial intelligence\")]\n[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/e/e6/Shannon_and_mouse.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shannon_and_mouse.png)Shannon and his [electromechanical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromechanical \"Electromechanical\") mouse _Theseus_ (named after [Theseus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theseus \"Theseus\") from Greek mythology) which he tried to have solve the maze in one of the first experiments in [artificial intelligence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence \"Artificial intelligence\")\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=7 \"Edit section: Theseus, the mouse\")]\nIn 1950, Shannon designed and built, with the help of his wife, Betty, a learning machine named Theseus. It consisted of a maze on a surface, through which a mechanical mouse could move. Below the surface were sensors (an electromechanical relay circuit)[[66]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Bell_Labs_acknowledgement-66) that followed the path of a mechanical mouse through the maze.[[29]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT-29) The mouse was designed to search through the corridors until it found the target.[[66]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Bell_Labs_acknowledgement-66) Having travelled through the maze, the mouse could then be placed anywhere it had been before, and because of its prior experience it could go directly to the target. If placed in unfamiliar territory, it was programmed to search until it reached a known location and then it would proceed to the target, adding the new knowledge to its memory and learning new behavior.[[66]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Bell_Labs_acknowledgement-66) After much trial and error, this device would learn the shortest path through the maze, and direct the mechanical mouse through the maze. The pattern of the maze could be changed at will,[[29]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT-29) by rearranging movable partitions.[[66]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Bell_Labs_acknowledgement-66) Shannon's mouse appears to have been the first artificial learning device of its kind.[[66]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Bell_Labs_acknowledgement-66)\n[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Theseus_Maze_by_Claude_Shannon%2C_1952_-_MIT_Museum_-_DSC03702.JPG/250px-Theseus_Maze_by_Claude_Shannon%2C_1952_-_MIT_Museum_-_DSC03702.JPG)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Theseus_Maze_by_Claude_Shannon,_1952_-_MIT_Museum_-_DSC03702.JPG)Theseus Maze in MIT Museum\n[Mazin Gilbert](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mazin_Gilbert \"Mazin Gilbert\") stated that Theseus \"inspired the whole field of AI. This random trial and error is the foundation of artificial intelligence.\"[[29]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT-29)\n#### Other artificial intelligence work\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=8 \"Edit section: Other artificial intelligence work\")]\nShannon wrote multiple influential papers on artificial intelligence, such as his 1950 paper titled \"Programming a Computer for Playing Chess\", and his 1953 paper titled \"Computers and Automata\".[[67]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-67) Alongside [John McCarthy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McCarthy_\\(computer_scientist\\) \"John McCarthy \\(computer scientist\\)\"), he co-edited a book titled _Automata Studies_ , which was published in 1956. The categories in the articles within the volume were influenced by Shannon's own subject headings in his 1953 paper. Shannon shared McCarthy's goal of creating a science of intelligent machines, but also held a broader view of viable approaches in automata studies, such as neural nets, Turing machines, cybernetic mechanisms, and symbolic processing by computer.[[60]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEEAnnalsComp-60)\nShannon co-organized and participated in the [Dartmouth workshop](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dartmouth_workshop \"Dartmouth workshop\") of 1956, alongside John McCarthy, [Marvin Minsky](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marvin_Minsky \"Marvin Minsky\") and [Nathaniel Rochester](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Rochester_\\(computer_scientist\\) \"Nathaniel Rochester \\(computer scientist\\)\"), and which is considered the founding event of the field of artificial intelligence.[[68]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-68)[[26]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Solomonoff-26)\n### Teaching at MIT\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=9 \"Edit section: Teaching at MIT\")]\nIn 1956 Shannon joined the MIT faculty, holding an endowed chair. He worked in the Research Laboratory of Electronics (RLE). He continued to serve on the MIT faculty until 1978.[[69]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-69)\n### Later life\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=10 \"Edit section: Later life\")]\nShannon developed [Alzheimer's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alzheimer%27s_disease \"Alzheimer's disease\") and spent the last few years of his life in a [nursing home](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nursing_home \"Nursing home\"); he died in 2001, survived by his wife, a son and daughter, and two granddaughters.[[70]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SW-70)[[71]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-71)\n### Hobbies and inventions\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=11 \"Edit section: Hobbies and inventions\")]\n[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Minivac_601.jpg/250px-Minivac_601.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Minivac_601.jpg)The [Minivac 601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minivac_601 \"Minivac 601\"), a digital computer trainer designed by Shannon\nOutside of Shannon's academic pursuits, he was interested in [juggling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juggling \"Juggling\"), [unicycling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicycling \"Unicycling\"), and [chess](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess \"Chess\"). He also invented many devices, including a [Roman numeral](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_numeral \"Roman numeral\") computer called THROBAC, and [juggling machines](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot_juggling \"Robot juggling\").[[72]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-72)[[73]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-73) He built a device that could solve the [Rubik's Cube](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubik%27s_Cube \"Rubik's Cube\") puzzle.[[33]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MIT_obituary-33)\nShannon also invented flame-throwing [trumpets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trumpet \"Trumpet\"), rocket-powered [frisbees](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frisbee \"Frisbee\"), and plastic foam [shoes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoe \"Shoe\") for navigating a lake, by wearing which it would appear to an observer as if Shannon were walking on water.[[74]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-74)\nShannon designed the [Minivac 601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minivac_601 \"Minivac 601\"), a [digital computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_computer \"Digital computer\") trainer to teach business people about how computers functioned. It was sold by the [Scientific Development Corp](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Scientific_Development_Corp&action=edit&redlink=1 \"Scientific Development Corp \\(page does not exist\\)\") starting in 1961.[[75]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-PS6110-75)\nHe is further considered the co-inventor of the first [wearable computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wearable_computer \"Wearable computer\") along with [Edward O. Thorp](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_O._Thorp \"Edward O. Thorp\").[[76]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Wearable_computer-76) The device was used to improve the odds when playing [roulette](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roulette \"Roulette\"). \n### Personal life\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=12 \"Edit section: Personal life\")]\nShannon married [Norma Levor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norma_Barzman \"Norma Barzman\"), a wealthy, Jewish, left-wing intellectual in January 1940. The marriage ended in divorce a year later. Levor later married [Ben Barzman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Barzman \"Ben Barzman\").[[77]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SoniGoodman-77)\nShannon met his second wife, [Mary Elizabeth Moore](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Shannon \"Betty Shannon\") (Betty), when she was a numerical analyst at Bell Labs. They were married in 1949.[[70]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-SW-70) Betty assisted Claude in building some of his most famous inventions.[[78]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-78) They had three children.[[79]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-79)\nShannon presented himself as [apolitical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apoliticism \"Apoliticism\") and an [atheist](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheism \"Atheism\").[[80]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-80)\n### Tributes and legacy\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=13 \"Edit section: Tributes and legacy\")]\n[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/AT%26T_Claude_Shannon_Statue_%28rotated%29.jpg/250px-AT%26T_Claude_Shannon_Statue_%28rotated%29.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AT%26T_Claude_Shannon_Statue_\\(rotated\\).jpg)Statue of Claude Shannon at AT&T Shannon Labs\nThere are six statues of Shannon sculpted by [Eugene Daub](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Daub \"Eugene Daub\"): one at the [University of Michigan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Michigan \"University of Michigan\"); one at MIT in the [Laboratory for Information and Decision Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_Laboratory_for_Information_and_Decision_Systems \"MIT Laboratory for Information and Decision Systems\"); one in Gaylord, Michigan; one at the [University of California, San Diego](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_California,_San_Diego \"University of California, San Diego\"); one at Bell Labs; and another at [AT&T Shannon Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AT%26T_Laboratories \"AT&T Laboratories\").[[81]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-81) The statue in Gaylord is located in the Claude Shannon Memorial Park.[[82]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-82) After the [breakup of the Bell System](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breakup_of_the_Bell_System \"Breakup of the Bell System\"), the part of Bell Labs that remained with [AT&T Corporation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AT%26T_Corporation \"AT&T Corporation\") was named Shannon Labs in his honor. \nIn June 1954, Shannon was listed as one of the top 20 most important scientists in America by _[Fortune](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortune_\\(magazine\\) \"Fortune \\(magazine\\)\")_.[[83]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Soni_Goodman_2017_p._62-83) In 2013, information theory was listed as one of the top 10 revolutionary scientific theories by _[Science News](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_News \"Science News\")_.[[84]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-84)\nAccording to [Neil Sloane](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Sloane \"Neil Sloane\"), an [AT&T Fellow](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=AT%26T_Fellow&action=edit&redlink=1 \"AT&T Fellow \\(page does not exist\\)\") who co-edited Shannon's large collection of papers in 1993, the perspective introduced by Shannon's communication theory (now called \"information theory\") is the foundation of the [digital revolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_Revolution \"Digital Revolution\"), and every device containing a [microprocessor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microprocessor \"Microprocessor\") or [microcontroller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microcontroller \"Microcontroller\") is a conceptual descendant of Shannon's publication in 1948:[[85]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-shannon_paper-85) \"He's one of the great men of the century. Without him, none of the things we know today would exist. The whole digital revolution started with him.\"[[86]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-star_ledger-86) The [cryptocurrency](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptocurrency \"Cryptocurrency\") unit shannon (a synonym for gwei, one billion [wei](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethereum#Ether \"Ethereum\")) is named after him.[[87]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-87)\nShannon is credited by many as single-handedly creating information theory and for laying the foundations for the [Digital Age](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_Age \"Information Age\").[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-QuantaMagazine-2)[[14]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEETransactions-14)[[88]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-88)[[89]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-89)[[90]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-90)[[91]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-91)\nHis achievements are considered to be on par with those of [Albert Einstein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein \"Albert Einstein\"), [Sir Isaac Newton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton \"Isaac Newton\"), and [Charles Darwin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Darwin \"Charles Darwin\").[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-BulletinESA-1)[[18]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune2-18)[[6]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEESpectrum4.27.16-6)[[92]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-ManWhoInventedIT-92)\n_[A Mind at Play](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Mind_at_Play \"A Mind at Play\")_ , a biography of Shannon written by [Jimmy Soni](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Soni \"Jimmy Soni\") and Rob Goodman, was published in 2017.[[93]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-93) They described Shannon as \"the most important genius you’ve never heard of, a man whose intellect was on par with [Albert Einstein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein \"Albert Einstein\") and [Isaac Newton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton \"Isaac Newton\")\".[[94]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-94) Consultant and writer Tom Rutledge, writing for [Boston Review](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston_Review \"Boston Review\"), stated that \"Of the computer pioneers who drove the mid-20th-century information technology revolution—an elite men’s club of scholar-engineers who also helped crack Nazi codes and pinpoint missile trajectories—Shannon may have been the most brilliant of them all.\"[[92]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-ManWhoInventedIT-92) Electrical engineer [Robert Gallager](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_G._Gallager \"Robert G. Gallager\") stated about Shannon that \"He had this amazing clarity of vision. Einstein had it, too – this ability to take on a complicated problem and find the right way to look at it, so that things become very simple.\"[[19]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-TechReview7.1.01-19) In an obituary by Neil Sloane and [Robert Calderbank](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Calderbank \"Robert Calderbank\"), they stated that \"Shannon must rank near the top of the list of major figures of twentieth century science\".[[95]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-95) Due to his work in multiple fields, Shannon is also regarded as a [polymath](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymath \"Polymath\").[[96]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-96)[[97]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-97)\nHistorian [James Gleick](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gleick \"James Gleick\") noted the importance of Shannon, stating that \"Einstein looms large, and rightly so. But we’re not living in the relativity age, we’re living in the information age. It’s Shannon whose fingerprints are on every electronic device we own, every computer screen we gaze into, every means of digital communication. He’s one of these people who so transform the world that, after the transformation, the old world is forgotten.\" Gleick further noted that \"he created a whole field from scratch, from the brow of [Zeus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeus \"Zeus\")\".[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-NewYorker4.30.16-3)\nOn April 30, 2016, Shannon was honored with a [Google Doodle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Doodle \"Google Doodle\") to celebrate his life on what would have been his 100th birthday.[[98]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-98)[[99]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Time-99)[[100]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Tech_Times-100)[[101]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Fortune_\\(magazine\\)-101)\n_[The Bit Player](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bit_Player \"The Bit Player\")_ , a feature film about Shannon directed by [Mark Levinson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Levinson_\\(film_director\\) \"Mark Levinson \\(film director\\)\") premiered at the [World Science Festival](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Science_Festival \"World Science Festival\") in 2019.[[102]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-physicstoday-102) Drawn from interviews conducted with Shannon in his house in the 1980s, the film was released on Amazon Prime in August 2020. \n[Claude](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_\\(language_model\\) \"Claude \\(language model\\)\"), the [large language model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_language_model \"Large language model\") developed by artificial intelligence research company [Anthropic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthropic \"Anthropic\"), is partially named in honor of Shannon.[[103]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-103)[[104]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-104)\n## _The Mathematical Theory of Communication_\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=14 \"Edit section: The Mathematical Theory of Communication\")]\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=15 \"Edit section: Weaver's Contribution\")]\nShannon's _The Mathematical Theory of Communication,_[[58]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-MathTheoryCommunication-58) begins with an interpretation of his own work by [Warren Weaver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warren_Weaver \"Warren Weaver\"). Although Shannon's entire work is about communication itself, Warren Weaver communicated his ideas in such a way that those not acclimated to complex theory and mathematics could comprehend the fundamental laws he put forth. The coupling of their unique communicational abilities and ideas generated the [Shannon-Weaver model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%E2%80%93Weaver_model \"Shannon–Weaver model\"), although the mathematical and theoretical underpinnings emanate entirely from Shannon's work after Weaver's introduction. For the layman, Weaver's introduction better communicates _The Mathematical Theory of Communication_ ,[[105]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-105) but Shannon's subsequent logic, mathematics, and expressive precision was responsible for defining the problem itself.[_[citation needed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")_]\n## Other work\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=16 \"Edit section: Other work\")]\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=17 \"Edit section: Shannon's estimate for the complexity of chess\")]\nMain article: [Shannon number](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_number \"Shannon number\")\nIn 1949 Shannon completed a paper (published in March 1950) which estimates the [game-tree complexity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_complexity \"Game complexity\") of [chess](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess \"Chess\"), which is approximately 10120. This number is now often referred to as the \"[Shannon number](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_number \"Shannon number\")\", and is still regarded today as an accurate estimate of the game's complexity. The number is often cited as one of the barriers to [solving the game of chess](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solving_chess \"Solving chess\") using an exhaustive analysis (i.e. [brute force analysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute-force_search \"Brute-force search\")).[[106]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-CS-106)[[107]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-107)\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=18 \"Edit section: Shannon's computer chess program\")]\nOn March 9, 1949, Shannon presented a paper called \"Programming a Computer for playing Chess\". The paper was presented at the National Institute for Radio Engineers Convention in New York. He described how to program a computer to play chess based on position scoring and move selection. He proposed basic strategies for restricting the number of possibilities to be considered in a game of chess. In March 1950 it was published in _[Philosophical Magazine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophical_Magazine \"Philosophical Magazine\")_ , and is considered one of the first articles published on the topic of programming a computer for playing chess, and using a computer to solve the game.[[106]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-CS-106)[[108]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-108) In 1950, Shannon wrote an article titled \"A Chess-Playing Machine\",[[109]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-109) which was published in _[Scientific American](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_American \"Scientific American\")._ Both papers have had immense influence and laid the foundations for future chess programs.[[27]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-CompSimBehavior-27)[[28]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-DebuggingGameHist-28)\nHis process for having the computer decide on which move to make was a [minimax](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimax \"Minimax\") procedure, based on an [evaluation function](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evaluation_function \"Evaluation function\") of a given chess position. Shannon gave a rough example of an evaluation function in which the value of the black position was subtracted from that of the white position. _Material_ was counted according to the usual [chess piece relative value](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_piece_relative_value \"Chess piece relative value\") (1 point for a pawn, 3 points for a knight or bishop, 5 points for a rook, and 9 points for a queen).[[110]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-110) He considered some positional factors, subtracting ½ point for each [doubled pawn](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doubled_pawn \"Doubled pawn\"), [backward pawn](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backward_pawn \"Backward pawn\"), and [isolated pawn](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isolated_pawn \"Isolated pawn\"); _[mobility](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobility_\\(chess\\) \"Mobility \\(chess\\)\")_ was incorporated by adding 0.1 point for each legal move available. \n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=19 \"Edit section: Shannon's maxim\")]\nShannon formulated a version of [Kerckhoffs' principle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerckhoffs%27s_principle \"Kerckhoffs's principle\") as \"The enemy knows the system\". In this form it is known as \"Shannon's maxim\". \n### Miscellaneous\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=20 \"Edit section: Miscellaneous\")]\nShannon also contributed to [combinatorics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics \"Combinatorics\") and [detection theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detection_theory \"Detection theory\"). His 1948 paper introduced many tools used in combinatorics. He did work on detection theory in 1944, with his work being one of the earliest expositions of the “matched filter” principle.[[111]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-111)\nHe was known as a successful investor who gave lectures on investing. A report from _[Barron's](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barron%27s \"Barron's\")_ on August 11, 1986, detailed the recent performance of 1,026 mutual funds, and Shannon achieved a higher return than 1,025 of them. Comparing the portfolio of Shannon from the late 1950s to 1986, to [Warren Buffett](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warren_Buffett \"Warren Buffett\")'s of 1965 to 1995, Shannon had a return of about 28%, compared to 27% for Buffett.[[112]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPoundstone2005307-112) One such method of Shannon's was labeled **Shannon's demon** , which was to form a portfolio of equal parts cash and a stock, and rebalance regularly to take advantage of the stock's randomly jittering price movements. Shannon reportedly long thought of publishing about investing, but ultimately did not, despite giving multiple lectures. He was one of the first investors to download stock prices, and a snapshot of his portfolio in 1981 was found to be $582,717.50, translating to $1.5 million in 2015, excluding another one of his stocks.[[113]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-113)\n## Commemorations\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=21 \"Edit section: Commemorations\")]\n### Shannon centenary\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=22 \"Edit section: Shannon centenary\")]  \n| ![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/60px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png)  | This section needs to be **updated**. Please help update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information. _( April 2016)_  |  \n| --- | --- |  \n[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Claude_Shannon_Centenary_Logo.jpg/250px-Claude_Shannon_Centenary_Logo.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Claude_Shannon_Centenary_Logo.jpg)Claude Shannon centenary\nThe Shannon centenary, 2016, marked the life and influence of Shannon on the hundredth anniversary of his birth on April 30, 1916. It was inspired in part by the [Alan Turing Year](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing_Year \"Alan Turing Year\"). An ad hoc committee of the [IEEE Information Theory Society](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Information_Theory_Society \"IEEE Information Theory Society\") including [Christina Fragouli](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christina_Fragouli \"Christina Fragouli\"), Rüdiger Urbanke, [Michelle Effros](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Effros \"Michelle Effros\"), Lav Varshney and [Sergio Verdú](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Verd%C3%BA \"Sergio Verdú\"),[[114]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-114) coordinated worldwide events. The initiative was announced in the History Panel at the 2015 IEEE Information Theory Workshop Jerusalem[[115]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-115)[[116]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-116) and the IEEE Information Theory Society newsletter.[[117]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-117)\nA detailed listing of confirmed events was available on the website of the IEEE Information Theory Society.[[118]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-118)\nSome of the activities included: \n  * [Bell Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\") hosted the First Shannon Conference on the Future of the Information Age on April 28–29, 2016, in Murray Hill, New Jersey, to celebrate Shannon and the continued impact of his legacy on society. The event includes keynote speeches by global luminaries and visionaries of the information age who will explore the impact of information theory on society and our digital future, informal recollections, and leading technical presentations on subsequent related work in other areas such as bioinformatics, economic systems, and social networks. There is also a student competition\n  * [Bell Labs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\") launched a web exhibit[[119]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-119) on April 30, 2016, chronicling Shannon's hiring at Bell Labs (under an NDRC contract with US Government), his subsequent work there from 1942 through 1957, and details of Mathematics Department. The exhibit also displayed bios of colleagues and managers during his tenure, as well as original versions of some of the technical memoranda which subsequently became well known in published form.\n  * The Republic of Macedonia issued a commemorative stamp.[[120]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-120) A [USPS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Postal_Service \"United States Postal Service\") commemorative stamp is being proposed, with an active petition.[[121]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-121)\n  * A documentary on Shannon and on the impact of information theory, [The Bit Player](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bit_Player \"The Bit Player\"), was produced by [Sergio Verdú](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Verd%C3%BA \"Sergio Verdú\") and [Mark Levinson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Levinson_\\(film_director\\) \"Mark Levinson \\(film director\\)\").[[122]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-122)\n  * A trans-Atlantic celebration of both George Boole's bicentenary and Shannon's centenary that is being led by University College Cork and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. A first event was a workshop in Cork, When Boole Meets Shannon,[[123]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-123) and will continue with exhibits at the [Boston Museum of Science](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Museum_of_Science_\\(Boston\\) \"Museum of Science \\(Boston\\)\") and at the [MIT Museum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_Museum \"MIT Museum\").[[124]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-124)\n  * Many organizations around the world are holding observance events, including the Boston Museum of Science, the Heinz-Nixdorf Museum, the Institute for Advanced Study, Technische Universität Berlin, University of South Australia (UniSA), Unicamp (Universidade Estadual de Campinas), University of Toronto, Chinese University of Hong Kong, Cairo University, Telecom ParisTech, National Technical University of Athens, Indian Institute of Science, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, [Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Institute_of_Technology_Kanpur \"Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur\"), [Nanyang Technological University](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanyang_Technological_University \"Nanyang Technological University\") of Singapore, University of Maryland, University of Illinois at Chicago, École Polytechnique Federale de Lausanne, The Pennsylvania State University (Penn State), University of California Los Angeles, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, [Chongqing University of Posts and Telecommunications](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chongqing_University_of_Posts_and_Telecommunications \"Chongqing University of Posts and Telecommunications\"), and University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.\n  * A logo that appears on this page was crowdsourced on Crowdspring.[[125]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-125)\n  * The Math Encounters presentation of May 4, 2016, at the [National Museum of Mathematics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Museum_of_Mathematics \"National Museum of Mathematics\") in New York, titled _Saving Face: Information Tricks for Love and Life_ , focused on Shannon's work in information theory. A video recording and other material are available.[[126]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-126)\n\n\n## Awards and honors list\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=23 \"Edit section: Awards and honors list\")]\nThe [Claude E. Shannon Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_E._Shannon_Award \"Claude E. Shannon Award\") was established in his honor; he was also its first recipient, in 1973.[[127]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-127)[[128]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-Roberts-128)\n  * [Stuart Ballantine Medal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_Ballantine_Medal \"Stuart Ballantine Medal\") of the [Franklin Institute](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franklin_Institute \"Franklin Institute\"), 1955[[129]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-129)\n  * Member of the [American Academy of Arts and Sciences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences \"American Academy of Arts and Sciences\"), 1957[[130]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-130)\n  * [Harvey Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Prize \"Harvey Prize\"), the [Technion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technion \"Technion\") of [Haifa](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haifa \"Haifa\"), [Israel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel \"Israel\"), 1972[[131]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-admin.technion.ac.il-131)\n  * [Alfred Noble Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Noble_Prize \"Alfred Noble Prize\"), 1939 (award of civil engineering societies in the US)[[132]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-ASCE-132)\n  * [National Medal of Science](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Medal_of_Science \"National Medal of Science\"), 1966, presented by President [Lyndon B. Johnson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyndon_B._Johnson \"Lyndon B. Johnson\")[[133]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-133)\n  * [Kyoto Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyoto_Prize \"Kyoto Prize\"), 1985[[134]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-134)\n  * [Morris Liebmann Memorial Prize](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morris_Liebmann_Memorial_Prize \"Morris Liebmann Memorial Prize\") of the [Institute of Radio Engineers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Radio_Engineers \"Institute of Radio Engineers\"), 1949[[135]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-IEEE-Liebmann-Award-Recipients-135)\n  * United States [National Academy of Sciences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Academy_of_Sciences \"National Academy of Sciences\"), 1956[[136]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-National_Academy_of_Sciences_2015-136)\n  * [Medal of Honor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Medal_of_Honor \"IEEE Medal of Honor\") of the [Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Electrical_and_Electronics_Engineers \"Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers\"), 1966[[137]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-137)\n  * Golden Plate Award of the [American Academy of Achievement](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_of_Achievement \"Academy of Achievement\"), 1967[[138]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-138)\n  * [Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Netherlands_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences \"Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences\") (KNAW), foreign member, 1975[[139]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-139)\n  * Member of the [American Philosophical Society](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Philosophical_Society \"American Philosophical Society\"), 1983[[140]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-140)\n  * Member of the [Royal Irish Academy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Irish_Academy \"Royal Irish Academy\"), 1985[[141]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-141)\n  * Member of the [US National Academy of Engineering](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Academy_of_Engineering \"National Academy of Engineering\") (1985)[[142]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-142)\n  * [Basic Research Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduard_Rhein_Award \"Eduard Rhein Award\"), [Eduard Rhein Foundation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduard_Rhein_Foundation \"Eduard Rhein Foundation\"), [Germany](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany \"Germany\"), 1991[[143]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-143)\n  * [Marconi Society Lifetime Achievement Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marconi_Prize \"Marconi Prize\"), 2000[[144]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-144)\n  * [Donner Professor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Donner \"William Donner\") of Science, MIT, 1958–1979[[145]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_note-145)\n\n\n## Selected works\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=24 \"Edit section: Selected works\")]\n  * Claude E. Shannon: _[A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Symbolic_Analysis_of_Relay_and_Switching_Circuits \"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits\")_ , [master's thesis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Master%27s_thesis \"Master's thesis\"), MIT, 1937.\n  * Claude E. Shannon: \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\", _Bell System Technical Journal_ , Vol. 27, pp. 379–423, 623–656, 1948 ([abstract](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=6773024&tag=1)).\n  * Claude E. Shannon and Warren Weaver: _The Mathematical Theory of Communication._ The University of Illinois Press, Urbana, Illinois, 1949. [ISBN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISBN \\(identifier\\)\") [0-252-72548-4](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-252-72548-4 \"Special:BookSources/0-252-72548-4\")\n  * [Neil Sloane](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Sloane \"Neil Sloane\") editor (1993) [_Claude Shannon: Collected Works_](http://neilsloane.com/doc/shannon.html), [IEEE Press](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Press \"IEEE Press\")\n\n\n## See also\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=25 \"Edit section: See also\")]\n  * ![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/69/P_vip.svg/40px-P_vip.svg.png)[Biography portal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Biography \"Portal:Biography\")\n  * [![icon](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Nuvola_apps_edu_mathematics_blue-p.svg/40px-Nuvola_apps_edu_mathematics_blue-p.svg.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nuvola_apps_edu_mathematics_blue-p.svg)[Mathematics portal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Mathematics \"Portal:Mathematics\")\n\n\n  * [Entropy power inequality](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_power_inequality \"Entropy power inequality\")\n  * [Error-correcting codes with feedback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error-correcting_codes_with_feedback \"Error-correcting codes with feedback\")\n  * [List of pioneers in computer science](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_pioneers_in_computer_science \"List of pioneers in computer science\")\n  * [Models of communication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Models_of_communication \"Models of communication\")\n  * [n-gram](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N-gram \"N-gram\")\n  * [Noisy channel coding theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noisy_channel_coding_theorem \"Noisy channel coding theorem\")\n  * [Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist%E2%80%93Shannon_sampling_theorem \"Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem\")\n  * [One-time pad](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-time_pad \"One-time pad\")\n  * [Product cipher](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_cipher \"Product cipher\")\n  * [Pulse-code modulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-code_modulation \"Pulse-code modulation\")\n  * [Rate distortion theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rate_distortion_theory \"Rate distortion theory\")\n  * [Sampling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_\\(signal_processing\\) \"Sampling \\(signal processing\\)\")\n  * [Shannon capacity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_capacity_\\(disambiguation\\) \"Shannon capacity \\(disambiguation\\)\")\n  * [Shannon entropy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_entropy \"Shannon entropy\")\n  * [Shannon index](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_index \"Shannon index\")\n  * [Shannon multigraph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_multigraph \"Shannon multigraph\")\n  * [Shannon security](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_security \"Shannon security\")\n  * [Shannon switching game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_switching_game \"Shannon switching game\")\n  * [Shannon–Fano coding](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%E2%80%93Fano_coding \"Shannon–Fano coding\")\n  * [Shannon–Hartley law](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%E2%80%93Hartley_law \"Shannon–Hartley law\")\n  * [Shannon–Hartley theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%E2%80%93Hartley_theorem \"Shannon–Hartley theorem\")\n  * [Shannon's expansion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%27s_expansion \"Shannon's expansion\")\n  * [Shannon's source coding theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%27s_source_coding_theorem \"Shannon's source coding theorem\")\n  * [Shannon-Weaver model of communication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon%E2%80%93Weaver_model \"Shannon–Weaver model\")\n  * [Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whittaker%E2%80%93Shannon_interpolation_formula \"Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula\")\n\n\n## References\n[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Claude_Shannon&action=edit&section=26 \"Edit section: References\")]\n  1. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-BulletinESA_1-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-BulletinESA_1-1) Atmar, Wirt (2001). \"A Profoundly Repeated Pattern\". _Bulletin of the Ecological Society of America_. **82** (3): 208–211. [ISSN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISSN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISSN \\(identifier\\)\") [0012-9623](https://search.worldcat.org/issn/0012-9623). [JSTOR](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JSTOR_\\(identifier\\) \"JSTOR \\(identifier\\)\") [20168572](https://www.jstor.org/stable/20168572).\n  2. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-QuantaMagazine_2-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-QuantaMagazine_2-1) [_**c**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-QuantaMagazine_2-2) [Tse, David](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Tse \"David Tse\") (December 22, 2020). [\"How Claude Shannon Invented the Future\"](https://www.quantamagazine.org/how-claude-shannons-information-theory-invented-the-future-20201222/). _Quanta_. Retrieved September 28, 2023.\n  3. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-NewYorker4.30.16_3-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-NewYorker4.30.16_3-1) [Roberts, Siobhan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siobhan_Roberts \"Siobhan Roberts\") (April 30, 2016). [\"The Forgotten Father of the Information Age\"](https://www.newyorker.com/tech/annals-of-technology/claude-shannon-the-father-of-the-information-age-turns-1100100). _[The New Yorker](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_Yorker \"The New Yorker\")_. [ISSN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISSN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISSN \\(identifier\\)\") [0028-792X](https://search.worldcat.org/issn/0028-792X). Retrieved September 28, 2023.\n  4. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-PortraitsInSilicon_4-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-PortraitsInSilicon_4-1) Slater, Robert (1989). [_Portraits in Silicon_](https://books.google.com/books?id=aWTtMyYmKhUC&pg=PA37). Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press. pp. 37–38. [ISBN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_\\(identifier\\) \"ISBN \\(identifier\\)\") [978-0-262-69131-4](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-262-69131-4 \"Special:BookSources/978-0-262-69131-4\").\n  5. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-bmfrs_5-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-bmfrs_5-1) [_**c**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-bmfrs_5-2) [James, Ioan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ioan_James \"Ioan James\") (2009). [\"Claude Elwood Shannon, 30 April 1916 – 24 February 2001\"](https://doi.org/10.1098%2Frsbm.2009.0015). _[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biographical_Memoirs_of_Fellows_of_the_Royal_Society \"Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society\")_. **55** (55): 257–265. [doi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doi_\\(identifier\\) \"Doi \\(identifier\\)\"):[10.1098/rsbm.2009.0015](https://doi.org/10.1098%2Frsbm.2009.0015).\n  6. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-IEEESpectrum4.27.16_6-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-IEEESpectrum4.27.16_6-1) [Horgan, John](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Horgan_\\(journalist\\) \"John Horgan \\(journalist\\)\") (April 27, 2016). [\"Claude Shannon: Tinkerer, Prankster, and Father of Information Theory\"](https://spectrum.ieee.org/claude-shannon-tinkerer-prankster-and-father-of-information-theory). _IEEE Spectrum_. Retrieved September 28, 2023.\n  7. ^ [Jump up to: _**a**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-IEEESpectrum1.25.22_7-0) [_**b**_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon#cite_ref-IEEESpectrum1.25.22_7-1) [Brooks, Rodney](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Brooks \"Rodney Brooks\") (January 25, 2022). [\"How Claude Shannon Helped Kick-start Machine Learning\"](https://spectrum.ieee.org/claude-shannon-information-theory). _IEEE Spectrum_